OL,7,FA crucial system of ocean currents
OL,8,Fthat helps maintain the world's
OL,9,Fclimate may already be on course to a
OL,10,Ftipping point, scientists have warned.
OL,11,FKnown as the Atlantic Meridional
OL,12,FOverturning Circulation (Amoc), this
OL,13,Fnetwork of deep and surface currents
OL,14,Fhelp keep temperatures milder in the
OL,15,FUK and Western Europe compared to
OL,16,Fother regions at similar latitudes `
OL,17,Fsuch as parts of eastern Canada as
OL,18,Fwell as Siberia.JScientists say a
OL,19,Fbreakdown of this system could
OL,20,Fpotentially plunge the UK and large
OL,21,Fparts of the Northern Hemisphere into
OL,22,Fa new ice age ` an outcome that was
OL,23,Fdramatised in the 2004 Hollywood
OL,24,Fblockbuster The Day After Tomorrow.JIt
OL,25,Fwould also disrupt rainfall that
OL,26,Fbillions rely on for agriculture,
