OL,7,FThe Amoc plays a key role in
OL,8,Fregulating Earth's climate by
OL,9,Ftransporting heat from the Equator
OL,10,Ftowards the Poles.JHowever, as global
OL,11,Ftemperatures rise due to warming,
OL,12,Ffreshwater is pouring into the system
OL,13,Ffrom the melting ice from Antarctica,
OL,14,FGreenland and other sources, risking
OL,15,Fdisruption to the circulation patterns
OL,16,Fthat drive the Amoc.JDr Van Westen,
OL,17,Falong with a team of researchers at
OL,18,FUtrecht University, designed a
OL,19,Fsimulation where they gradually
OL,20,Fintroduced surface freshwater over the
OL,21,Fcourse of 2,200 model years.JThe
OL,22,Ffindings, published in the journal
OL,23,FScience Advances, showed a gradual
OL,24,Fdecline of the Amoc over 1700 model
OL,25,Fyears, followed by an abrupt tipping
OL,26,Fevent beginning around the year 1758
